h engineers to harness the socially transformative power of this science-based enterprise. A centralized plan of electrification triumphed, to the benefit of the Communist Party and the detriment of local governments and the electrical engineers. Coopersmith's narrative of how this came to be elucidates the deep-seated and chronic conflict between the utopianism of Soviet ideology and the reality of Soviet politics and economics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aElectric industriesxSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aElectric industrieszSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aElectric industries. 0aElectrificationxEconomic aspectsxSoviet Union. 0aElectrificationxEconomic aspectszSoviet Union. 0aElectrification. 4aHistory Of Technology. 4aHistory. 4aSoviet & East European History. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749340uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501705373?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501705373zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501705373/original  a978-3-11-053617-1 Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  a978-3-11-066749-3 Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA